segments.text: First, Mr. McQuillan, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, and the places of their birth, the place and date of your birth, and the schools you attended before you came to Texas A&M.
Well, my father's name was James E. McQuillan.
My mother's name was Aiden McQuillan, and I don't have the dates of their death.
He worked for the Santa Fe Railroad, and we lived all up and down the Santa Fe Railroad in Texas.
I started school in Gainesville, Texas.
And then we moved to Sillsby, Texas, where I went to school.
And then we moved to Cleburne, Texas, where I graduated from Cleburne High School.
I entered here in the fall of 1916.
Where were you born?
I was born in Palestine, Texas.
And on what date?
June the 9th, 1898.
And I entered here in the fall of 16 and graduated in the spring of 1920.
And then I went to the University of Wisconsin for a year and got a master's degree and came back here and taught in the animal husbandry department for a year.
What were the factors involved in your choice of Texas A&M?
Well, largely because I didn't have to take any math.
I mean, you could go through the full four-year curriculum.
At that time, you could without taking any mathematics.
Without taking any math.
I didn't want any mathematics.
That is like everything else.
Things happen.
I didn't know what I was going to do in the spring of my senior year, and Dr. Brazell came by.
Well, we used to sit under the trees out there in front of Leggett Hall.
after supper, and he walked by there one day and asked me what I was going to do, and I said, I didn't know.
He said, how would you like to go to the University of Wisconsin and take a master's degree?
I said, well, that sounds pretty good.
He said, if you'll do that, and then you come back here, I'll give you a job, pay you $2,400 a year.
That sounds like lots of money.
So that's the way that happened.
And it happened that way.
I came back here and stayed a year.
Then I went to Dallas.
and was in the insurance business for three years.
Then I came back here in the fall of 1925 as assistant to Colonel Ashburn, who was secretary of the Ag Students Association.
How much did you know about Texas A&M before you enrolled as a student?
Oh, practically nothing.
What were your first reactions when you arrived on campus?
Well, I thought to mess all food about it.
Did you have any... Let me rephrase this.
Were there any people to meet?
I'm assuming you came by train.
Were there any people there to meet, to train, to try to recruit you for a particular dorm or for a particular military company?
Well, no, but there was a senior here from Cleburne that I knew, and I had come down here to attract meat.
And I was what, in those days, they designated his fish.
And I went, I'm sure, to his company, which was B-2nd Infantry.
But there was no reception at all.
We got off the train, went up there and found a place.
And then presumably registered almost immediately.
And B-2nd was assigned to what dormitory?
Legget Hall.
Legget Hall, one of the newer ones.
So you missed out on some of the good things like carrying water and wood and all that sort of good stuff.
Yeah, that's right.
We had a deluxe accommodation, you know what I'm saying?
Would you describe a typical day when you were a student?
And I imagine you had over the four years and viewed the fact that the whole campus was turned into a military camp for one period of time.
But would you kind of describe a typical day during your student days as the time you got up and what you did during the day and the time you went to bed?
Well, the first two years, I guess.
Certainly the first year.
got up at Reveille and had calisthenics.
And then we went to breakfast and then to classes.
And when taps blew at night, all the lights went out, and that was that.
It was a strictly military organization.
It wasn't us.
They weren't very strict, but everything was done by Bugle.
I missed out on, in the earlier days, they used to form the cadet corps, which was a whole student body then, out in front of the old main building, and they'd march into class for that.
We didn't do that.
You just marched to meals.
Oh, yes, we marched to meals.
But not to classes.
May I pardon?
But not to classes.
Not to classes, no.
Did you march to the chapel on Sunday morning?
On Sunday morning, we marched to chapel.
I see.
So you were in both the old chapel and in Guyon Hall, I believe, probably, were you not?
Yes, yes.
Guyon was built in 18, I believe.
Yeah.
There was so much disturbance, and it gradually increased.
So much disturbance, I think, along my latter years.
That's when they started making chapel voluntary.
Uh-huh.
But you mean disturbance?
Oh, they'd cough in and throat clearing in the old chapel.
I don't remember whether there were wooden floors or not, but boys...
would put a match or a pencil down on the floor and roll it under their foot.
Wasn't real now, but sort of, you know.
Get enough of them doing it.
Distant thunder, you know.
I doubt if any of us profited much from the chapel exercises.
Well, oftentimes it required chapel very much.
But then, and so they, in your later years, chapel was voluntary then.
Voluntary, I believe, my last year.
You mentioned you thought that the food in the mess hall was pretty good.
Yeah.
How would, could you expand on that?
Well.
Tell us a little bit about what you did get to eat.
The main thing I can remember that we got to eat was toast.
They toasted those great big pieces of bread.
I don't know how they did it.
I never had seen any kind of toast like that when I was growing up.
And I grew up in an average family.
And then once a week we used to have steaks.
And we always had dessert.
Of course, I was always a hungry fellow.
I had no trouble with hot cakes, you know, for breakfast and things of that sort.
I thought it was fine.
Did you get much dessert when you were a fish?
Well, from time to time, yeah.
But you did have to give it up occasionally.
You had to give it up occasionally, yeah.
Did you ever have any prune rices?
Any what?
Any prune races in the mess hall when you were there?
No.
What was life like in the dormitory?
Was it pretty docile or pretty hectic?
Well, I think it was pretty much up to the individual, really.
If he let other people alone, they let him alone.
We always, I can remember, they're always in any, on any floor,
There were, oh, you call them hell raisers or whatnot, noisy and running around the hallways.
But if you wanted to study, well, they let you alone.
Did you have a guard mount every night?
Yeah.
Was that for all four years, or did they change it?
No, I think just for the first couple of years.
The war came along then, you know, and that changed a lot of things.
So they discontinued the...
What did the students do for entertainment and recreation?
Oh, sat around and pulled and of course everybody in those days was very much interested in athletics.
You wouldn't miss an athletic event of any kind.
I'm not sure just when it started, probably built while I was in school.
We had a, we called it the Airdrome, which is over where the chapel is now, the Chapel of Meditation and Prayer.
They had picture shows a couple of nights a week.
And of course, dances were a big thing in those days, but there weren't too many of them.
How many, do you remember, how many did you have
Oh, let's see, we think we had a Thanksgiving dance, and we had an RV dance, and a final ball.
Those were the big ones, and I guess scattered around probably, but there were no smaller dances like a departmental group or anything of that sort.
What about individual classes?
I think now some of the individual classes, like the freshmen, juniors, and seniors or something, have a dance.
Well, we had a junior ball.
The juniors had a banquet, and I guess with a dance afterwards.
I don't remember the dance part particularly.
I believe in connection with the junior banquet, I just checked the longhorn for your senior year, and I believe
there was some indication that you were a master or toastmaster at that junior banquet, at a junior banquet.
Yeah, that's right.
I believe there was some mention made of your being conducted into the mess hall by a brilliant plan.
Well, the big deal in those days was for the sophomores to kidnap the junior toastmaster.
To start with, they had to find out who he was.
And, uh,
It just got worse and worse as an activity carried to extreme.
And it got to where they'd send her on maybe four or five and kidnap all of them.
They did not kidnap me.
I had some friends here on the campus and a classmate.
who was kin to them, and they hid me in their house where they lived up on the campus, and spirited me into the mess hall without any trouble really, and I put on woman's clothes and walked on in.
You were in disguise then.
It had been hinted to me that there was this tradition, so to speak, of kidnapping the Toastmaster.
Was the toastmaster for the junior banquet a junior?
Yes, I'm sure he was.
So it would have been in your junior year that you were toastmaster for the junior banquet.
And I had understood that the sophomores attempted to kidnap this person.
They were quite elaborate.
It just got to be a nuisance.
And the college finally just said, you're not going to have any more of that.
Just discontinued the junior banquet then.
What was the procedure of choosing a toastmaster?
I don't know.
You don't remember?
I don't know, I guess.
class elected them, I don't know.
Well it would have had to been by secret ballot and only a select few would know then who it was.
We know that you know the upperclassmen and primarily say the sophomores but the rest of them could
choose a fish as their man, and that kind of gave them the privilege of assigning duties of one sort or another to the freshmen.
But can you tell us about any other kinds of privileges that upperclassmen had as opposed to what freshmen might do?
No, and the practice of freshmen
doing room service, orderly work, that came after my time.
I think it was just starting, probably my last year.
I never was in anybody's room orderly.
But that got to be pretty worrisome, too.
Pretty.
I mean, making the beds and getting a whole room ready for inspection.
Sweeping out the room.
Cleaning rifles and...
Do what?
Cleaning rifles.
Yeah, just do anything that the sophomore wanted to.
I don't know just how long that lasted.
It finally played out.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
And if so, could you tell us a little bit about them?
Well, John Burns, of course, was my senior instructor.
He was head of the age department, and we all were very fond of him.
Tommy Mayo, I don't know that I ever had a class under Tommy Mayo, but I have always felt like, as a teacher, he exerted more influence on more students than any professor I knew.
Of course, in those days, and I think it, I don't know how it is right now, but it got to where it was just the opposite.
We went overboard on ingratiating ourselves with your teacher.
That fell into ill repute somewhere along the line later.
That was brown noses, you know, and stuff like that.
But I used to figure when I could get that teacher to call me Mac, I had it made.
And I wasn't about to do anything that I thought he didn't like.
But that's frown, I don't know whether it still is or not, but for many, many years, that was very, that's frowned on, you know.
I'm not sure.
I guess it isn't quite as much frowned upon as it once was.
Well, I hope not, because it's a silly sort of a thing.
Yeah.
Did the teachers commonly refer to the students as, like, Mr. McQuillan?
Or did they use your given name?
Well, I think occasionally they did.
But I would guess that most of them just called you your last name, or your nickname, or your given name.
But if you could get the professor or instructor to use your nickname, you would have it more...
I thought I had it made.
You mentioned Dr. Bazell somewhat earlier in the statement he had made to you as your senior year.
What, in general, were the attitudes
of the students toward Dr. Buzell as president?
I think real fine, real fine.
He was an excitable man, really.
He got excited about Haitian and one thing or another, but he was very human, and I think that he had, during my time, had an excellent relationship with student body.
He was able to make the transition from being president of an all-girls school to an all-male military school reasonably well.
He'd been there, what, two or three years by the time you first came in, in 14, I believe.
What about the commandant?
Well, he was fair game for everybody.
Just to give them considerable trouble.
In what kind of, what types of ways did you give him trouble?
Oh, just dislike and occasionally throwing rocks at his house.
That was very seldom as far as I know, but did happen.
But just didn't like the commandant.
Who was commandant?
Well, Colonel Muller was the principal commandant when I was in school.
He was a tough disciplinarian, but we came to have a pretty sound respect for him.
He was fair.
He was a martinet, but he got along pretty good.
But you did try to give him a hard time occasionally.
Yeah.
Well, of course, in those days, kids were less inclined, I think, to rebel.
Well, it's like mess hall food.
Now, of course, all through the years, there's been a complaint about mess hall food.
Less now, I hear, than any time I can remember.
But by and large, we thought it was pretty good eating.
Yeah, well, I presume that...
The complaints would stem primarily from the lack of variety as opposed to insufficient quantity and bad taste of it.
I think they have such a wide variety now that most of them probably never ate so well in their lives.
One of the things which I feel makes Texas A&M the unique school that it is is the number of traditions which are carried on by the student body.
Do you remember during your years as a student, did you have a bonfire, yell practice, silver taps?
We had yell practice, and I don't think we had a bonfire when I was in school.
I don't remember one.
I never did work on one.
I think we had silver taps.
I think they've embellished it since then.
I don't think we went out and formed anything of that sort.
I think it's blue silver taps.
Whenever someone, whenever a student died.
I think it's like so many of those things, they add on to them year by year by year.
It's sort of like the bonfire.
I think, as far as I can remember, one of the earlier days, if they had a bonfire with just a few apple barrels, apple crates piled up out there in Drillfield and all of us cutting down trees.
What about muster?
I don't recall anything about the muster when I was in school.
We didn't have a student muster.
As there is now.
Yeah.
As a matter of fact, we built that tradition up.
There had been a tradition for many years about A&M clubs meeting on April 21st.
promoted particularly didn't amount to much and sometime along I guess in the late 30s or early 40s we decided we could build that thing up to a major proposition and we did.
But I don't recall it.
The story I'd heard about the student body in 1903 wanting to have a ceremony of some sort to celebrate Texas' independence.
Well, they wanted a holiday is what they wanted.
And I had understood that was the origin of the annual muster.
Yeah, that was.
And I think that's pretty well established.
That actually happened.
They marched on the president's house.
But as I say, because they weren't going to have any holiday.
And my guess is that some student got up and said, let's go over and ask the president about this business.
And we really went.
And he got out pretty good and said, well, we'll take a holiday this morning.
Let's go back to class this afternoon.
And from here on out, though, we're going to have a celebration on April 21st.
So that's the way it started.
But it smoldered along all those years until we got rid of building up.
Now, whereas they had a holiday and not much of a ceremony, today we have a big ceremony and no holiday.
That was the middle of the ceremony.
What about airing out?
Did you get aired out a number of times when you were a fish?
No.
No, that's another later development.
I don't have any recollection of any airing out.
Well, it might have been just in your particular dormitory that you weren't aired out.
I was going to say, I'm sure there was a tremendous difference in dormitories or military units.
We know that from time to time there were girls attending classes.
Did you have any girls in any classes that you attended?
No.
Do you know of any girls who were on campus in classes when you were a student?
No, I don't believe I did.
Someone told me just recently that

that there was a continuing increase in the number of girls under Dr. Bazell's administration as president, and that his desire to increase the number of girls was one of the factors in his departure.
Oh, I doubt that.
After all, he was offered a job at a major state university that I think
entirely logical that he accepted it.
Step up the ladder.
That's right, yeah.
Now, Bazell was not one to hold back on a scrap.
He battled the board of directors or anybody else, but I don't, I never did know of any particular trouble he got into.
Well, I didn't,
I really had the impression that he was in trouble, but that there might have been some pressure.
I would guess that his inclination was all towards the girls.
He was a very liberal man, I mean by that.
He was a humanistic man as compared to engineering, something of that sort.
Okay.
I noted in your clippings about you and your write-up in the Longhorn that you participated in athletics quite a bit.
Did the students who were on the college teams enjoy privileges that the normal students didn't have?
Well, I think only we had a training table.
That's as far as I know it, but I think that was just regular food.
It was just served at separate times, separate hours.
This would accommodate your practices.
I presume occasionally you were able to misdrill because of practice, but generally you had to abide by the other rules that the students had.
We know that a lot of students worked while they were in school.
Did you ever have a job while you were in school?
Oh, I had various odd jobs.
I cleaned test tubes in the biology department once a term, and I maintained tennis courts another term, but nothing regular.
I wasn't what I'd call a working student.
Well, I could imagine with
the amount of practice you would have to do in basketball, and I think you ran track one year or so.
You would occupy a lot of your time.
You wouldn't have much time for working.
Well, of course, there again, finance was so simple in those days.
You paid your fee at the beginning of school, and that carries you through the semester.
And it's covered board, room, and laundry.
And you already had your uniform, and there wasn't much spent money for.
Oh, we had a lot of students working, but then it wasn't the financial struggle that it is today, if you went at all.
Of course, there were always a few students that did struggle, and I guess just lived from hand to mouth, practically, but there weren't very many of them.
Much of that came a little bit later, I would imagine, during the Depression, in the project houses and that sort of thing.
